<div class="slide">
	<h1>2010</h1>
	<h2>Web FOO</h2>
	<p class="big center">Flickr, Facebook, Twitter, YouTube.</p>
    <p class="center">The Web has become a big hack to accommodate the needs of
        internet applications.</p>
</div>

<div class="slide">
	<h1>2010 continued</h1>
	<ul>
	<li>There are about 252 million people in the US between the ages 10 - 79.</li>
	<li>There are probably about <a href="http://www.facebook.com/press/info.php?statistics">165 million Facebook users in the US</a></li>
	<li>There are about <a href="http://mashable.com/2010/01/11/twitter-growth-stats/">23 million Twitter users in the US</a></li>
	<li>In the US Yahoo! email has 106 million users, Windows Live 47 million, Gmail
	37 million, and AOL 36.4 million. This all accounts for
	<a href="http://www.email-marketing-reports.com/metrics/email-statistics.htm">226 million total web email users in the US</a></li>
	<li>3 million businesses (which account for more than 30 million user accounts) have
	<a href="http://www.google.com/apps/intl/en/business/gogoogle.html">"gone Google"</a>.</li>
	</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
	<h1>2010 continued</h1>
	<p><img class="left" width="30%"src="../img/presentations/Mark_Zuckerberg_-_South_by_Southwest_2008_-_2-crop.jpg" alt="Mark Zuckerberg" title="" /></p>
	<p>Zuck announces that Facebook has 500 million users on July 21st, 2010.</p>

	<ul class="citations">
	<li><a href="http://blog.facebook.com/blog.php?post=409753352130">Zuckerberg blog post</a></li>
	<li><a href="http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Mark_Zuckerberg_-_South_by_Southwest_2008_-_2-crop.jpg">photo credit</a></li>
	</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
	<h1>Act II</h1>
	<p class="center big">You spend your day on the Internet; but <strong>not</strong> on the web.</p>
  <p class="center big">This is not a trivial distinction.</p>
</div>

<div class="slide">
